00:01:23.570 --> 00:01:25.880
today?

00:01:25.880 --> 00:01:27.780
It's great to be in Tucson.

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:29.930
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:29.930 --> 00:01:31.220
So thank you for inviting me.

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:33.770
And before I start,
there is one person

00:01:33.770 --> 00:01:36.140
that Joaquin forgot
to thank for all

00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:38.240
these extraordinary
lectures, which we have year,

00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:39.980
after year, after year.

00:01:39.980 --> 00:01:42.620
And it is a Joaquin Ruiz,
because none of that

00:01:42.620 --> 00:01:43.945
would happen without him.

00:01:43.945 --> 00:01:45.400
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:48.545
So thank you very much, Joaquin.

00:01:52.430 --> 00:01:55.197
So this is the last lecture
of this physics series,

00:01:55.197 --> 00:01:57.030
and I'm actually shocked
that there is still

00:01:57.030 --> 00:01:58.430
anybody in the room, because--

00:01:58.430 --> 00:02:00.250
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:03.170
--when I was a young, and
I would go to parties,

00:02:03.170 --> 00:02:06.570
and suddenly some lady
would come close to me,

00:02:06.570 --> 00:02:08.570
or people would come close
to me, and they'd go,

00:02:08.570 --> 00:02:09.289
what do you do?

00:02:09.289 --> 00:02:10.664
And I would say,
I'm a physicist.

00:02:10.664 --> 00:02:11.750
They would all walk away.

00:02:11.750 --> 00:02:14.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:16.780
So we had four
extraordinary lectures,

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:21.520
where the speakers
tried to explain

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:27.890
what we do to understand
what's next in physics.

00:02:27.890 --> 00:02:32.930
And what we've seen is
that a lot of this work

00:02:32.930 --> 00:02:35.780
is done in extraordinary
extreme conditions,

00:02:35.780 --> 00:02:40.240
be it near a neutron
star or a black hole,

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:43.790
or in these extraordinary
accelerators which are built--

00:02:43.790 --> 00:02:46.910
the LHC accelerator in Geneva.

00:02:46.910 --> 00:02:52.220
And really, to understand what
we don't understand in physics,

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:54.890
or in astronomy, we
have to, very often,

00:02:54.890 --> 00:02:58.100
go to these extraordinary
extreme conditions.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:02.180
But what I'd like to do today
is to take a step back, and tell

00:03:02.180 --> 00:03:06.890
you that things are even
extraordinary and bizarre and

00:03:06.890 --> 00:03:09.980
strange in our everyday life.

00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:13.610
And about 100 years ago,
very, very bright people

00:03:13.610 --> 00:03:17.000
invented a new theory
of physics, which

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:19.340
is called quantum mechanics.

00:03:19.340 --> 00:03:22.820
And I will show you that
quantum mechanics has

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:24.540
changed our lives completely.

00:03:24.540 --> 00:03:26.540
And you could not live
without quantum mechanics

00:03:26.540 --> 00:03:28.332
anymore, except you
don't know that,

00:03:28.332 --> 00:03:29.540
or you don't care about that.

00:03:29.540 --> 00:03:31.752
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:31.752 --> 00:03:33.710
But the other thing,
which is really important,

00:03:33.710 --> 00:03:36.980
is that, in addition
to changing our lives,

00:03:36.980 --> 00:03:40.160
quantum mechanics has
forced us to change

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:42.700
our deep understanding
and things like,

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:47.000
what is reality, what is
locality, and things like that.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:48.690
So let's see if it works.

00:03:48.690 --> 00:03:50.527
I'm a theorist, I
break everything.

00:03:50.527 --> 00:03:53.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:55.390 --> 00:03:57.900
I think Keith Dienes has
told you something very, very

00:03:57.900 --> 00:04:00.200
important about
what physicists do.

00:04:00.200 --> 00:04:03.520
And the first thing that we
do is we try to understand,

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:05.210
what are the rules of the game?

00:04:05.210 --> 00:04:08.600
What are the laws of nature?

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:11.140
And this is, again,
what, for instance,

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:14.330
we heard when we talked about
the LHC experiments, trying

00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:16.895
to discover new particles,
stuff beyond just

00:04:16.895 --> 00:04:18.589
than relative physics.

00:04:18.589 --> 00:04:21.110
But there is a lot more
to physics than that.

00:04:21.110 --> 00:04:23.696
And it's like if you play chess.

00:04:23.696 --> 00:04:25.070
If you play chess,
it's one thing

00:04:25.070 --> 00:04:28.940
to learn the rules of
how you move the pieces.

00:04:28.940 --> 00:04:30.860
But if you just
learn the rules, I

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:34.280
can bet you I know my grandson
is going to beat the heck out

00:04:34.280 --> 00:04:35.510
of you.

00:04:35.510 --> 00:04:37.220
Because he's learned
more than the rules.

00:04:37.220 --> 00:04:38.589
He's learned also strategies.

00:04:38.589 --> 00:04:40.130
He's learned how to
exploit the rule,

00:04:40.130 --> 00:04:42.920
how to understand their
profound implications,

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:44.630
and how to do stuff with that.

00:04:44.630 --> 00:04:46.810
And this is the second
part of physics.

00:04:46.810 --> 00:04:49.880
In parallel with the process
of discovering new laws,

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:51.710
we need to learn how
to use these rules,

00:04:51.710 --> 00:04:53.390
how to understand
what they mean.

00:04:53.390 --> 00:04:54.890
And this is a little
bit what I want

00:04:54.890 --> 00:04:58.910
to talk about today, the
second aspect of what

00:04:58.910 --> 00:05:01.400
makes physics so exciting.

00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:05.210
And basically, I will talk
to you about two mysteries.

00:05:05.210 --> 00:05:07.430
So there is a cat here.

00:05:07.430 --> 00:05:10.080
And this cat is here for
at least three reasons.

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:13.670
The first one is that cats
are very mysterious animals,

00:05:13.670 --> 00:05:17.030
and a lot of what we're going
to talk about is mysterious.

00:05:17.030 --> 00:05:20.270
We know the Cheshire cat, which
was a very strange cat in Alice

00:05:20.270 --> 00:05:21.500
in Wonderland.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:24.800
Most of you probably also know
about the Schrodinger cat,

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:27.920
which is both dead and alive.

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:32.360
And so I thought that,
if I keep this cat here,

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:34.929
on some of the slides,
this cat will come back.

00:05:34.929 --> 00:05:37.220
And this is a time when you
want to take a deep breath,

00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:39.241
because it's going to
become really weird.

00:05:39.241 --> 00:05:39.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:42.020
And I want you to think
a little bit this--

00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:46.660
so the cat is going to help
guide us through this business.

00:05:46.660 --> 00:05:50.810
And there are basically two
mysteries I want to talk about.

00:05:50.810 --> 00:05:52.760
The first one is
something that you may

00:05:52.760 --> 00:05:54.200
have heard about the bit more.

00:05:54.200 --> 00:05:57.730
It's called wave
particle duality.

00:05:57.730 --> 00:06:00.410
This was something
which was understood--

00:06:00.410 --> 00:06:03.910
not understood, but studied
about 100 years ago,

00:06:03.910 --> 00:06:05.200
90 years ago.

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:08.950
And basically, it tells you
that quantum objects are waves,

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:12.230
except if you look at them.

00:06:12.230 --> 00:06:15.010
So that's the first mystery
we're going to talk about.

00:06:15.010 --> 00:06:18.130
And the second mystery is
something Einstein called

00:06:18.130 --> 00:06:21.910
spooky action at a distance.

00:06:21.910 --> 00:06:24.530
And it has to do with the
fact that, in some situations,

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:28.090
you can have two particles,
one on the moon and one

00:06:28.090 --> 00:06:31.580
on the earth, or even
more unrealistically,

00:06:31.580 --> 00:06:34.410
one in San Francisco
and one in New York,

00:06:34.410 --> 00:06:37.440
and you cannot describe these
two particles independently.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:41.900
What a particle does profoundly
and instantaneously impacts

00:06:41.900 --> 00:06:43.610
the other particle.

00:06:43.610 --> 00:06:46.300
So this is the two mysteries.

00:06:46.300 --> 00:06:47.910
And the bottom
line of my lecture

00:06:47.910 --> 00:06:50.430
is going to be that
these two mysteries lead

00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:53.530
to two really key consequences.

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:56.040
The first one is that
we have to rethink

00:06:56.040 --> 00:06:58.970
what we mean by reality.

00:06:58.970 --> 00:07:01.370
And the second one
is that we will

00:07:01.370 --> 00:07:05.120
need to rethink what
we mean by locality.

00:07:05.120 --> 00:07:16.000
Reality is the idea that the
properties of objects exist,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.420
whether I look at them or not.

00:07:18.420 --> 00:07:23.370
So basically, Joaquin
exists with a beard,

00:07:23.370 --> 00:07:25.280
whether I look at him or not.

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:27.576
That's reality.

00:07:27.576 --> 00:07:31.020
Locality has to do with the
fact, which Einstein made very

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:35.580
clear, that no information
can propagate faster

00:07:35.580 --> 00:07:37.170
than the speed of light.

00:07:37.170 --> 00:07:42.710
And we're going to have
to revisit these two

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:45.830
self-evident
truths, if you want,

00:07:45.830 --> 00:07:48.926
in the context of
quantum mechanics.

00:07:48.926 --> 00:07:51.140
OK.

00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:54.550
So let's try to stop
a little bit slowly,

00:07:54.550 --> 00:07:58.510
and it's always a good idea to
start with talking about light.

00:07:58.510 --> 00:08:00.640
Because for
centuries, scientists

00:08:00.640 --> 00:08:02.830
have been worried quite
a bit about light.

00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:04.110
What is it light?

00:08:04.110 --> 00:08:06.316
How do we process images?

00:08:06.316 --> 00:08:07.690
All these kind of
optics of light

00:08:07.690 --> 00:08:09.900
are extremely fascinating.

00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:13.450
I could give a whole lecture,
or series of lectures, on that,

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:16.210
but I don't have time.

00:08:16.210 --> 00:08:19.090
So I will start at Newton.

00:08:19.090 --> 00:08:21.140
Newton was a cranky old man.

00:08:21.140 --> 00:08:23.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:26.810
And he was cranky, and
he looks cranky here.

00:08:26.810 --> 00:08:31.110
And he actually was one of
the most important scholars

00:08:31.110 --> 00:08:34.890
of optics, until the
18th and 19th century.

00:08:34.890 --> 00:08:37.919
He wrote a wonderful
book called Opticks,

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:40.289
where he studied the
reflection of light,

00:08:40.289 --> 00:08:41.460
the refraction of light.

00:08:41.460 --> 00:08:44.250
He studied how light, if you
put light through a prism,

00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:47.670
it gets broken into colors.

00:08:47.670 --> 00:08:53.100
And he came to the conclusion
that light was made out

00:08:53.100 --> 00:08:55.260
of streams of little particles.

00:08:55.260 --> 00:08:58.660
OK, that was his
view of the world.

00:08:58.660 --> 00:09:01.560
So light was
particles for Newton.

00:09:01.560 --> 00:09:05.480
And this view of
light stayed with us

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:09.470
for well over 100 years,
until another great character

00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:10.040
came around.

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:12.240
His name is Thomas Young.

00:09:12.240 --> 00:09:13.590
He was actually a polymath.

00:09:13.590 --> 00:09:15.430
He was a medical doctor.

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:17.610
He was very
interested in the eye.

00:09:17.610 --> 00:09:20.160
He's the first who understood
how the eye changes

00:09:20.160 --> 00:09:26.020
its shape so that we can focus
object at different distances.

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:30.480
He also was the first to
understand what astigmatism is.

00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:32.520
But in addition, he
was also an Egyptolog.

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:34.860
He made key development
which led then

00:09:34.860 --> 00:09:38.770
to the translation
of the Rosetta Stone

00:09:38.770 --> 00:09:41.310
by Champollion in France.

00:09:41.310 --> 00:09:43.680
And so he did all
kinds of things.

00:09:43.680 --> 00:09:45.100
He started in mechanics.

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:46.170
There's a wonderful book.

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:49.560
If you don't have anything to
do, you should read this book.

00:09:49.560 --> 00:09:51.240
The title of the
book, Thomas Young--

00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:53.560
The Last Man Who
Knew Everything.

00:09:53.560 --> 00:09:56.670
An absolutely remarkable book.

00:09:56.670 --> 00:10:00.060
And he studied life as well,
because he was interested

00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:01.880
in the eye, so,
therefore, he thought

00:10:01.880 --> 00:10:04.410
I need to study what light is.

00:10:04.410 --> 00:10:07.850
And he made a very simple
experiment, which I show here,

00:10:07.850 --> 00:10:11.730
where he took a little
screen, and he cut two slits

00:10:11.730 --> 00:10:16.070
into this screen, and
he shone a beam of light

00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:16.960
through that screen.

00:10:16.960 --> 00:10:18.890
A very, very simple experiment.

00:10:18.890 --> 00:10:21.290
And we all know what to expect
in this experiment, right?

00:10:21.290 --> 00:10:22.039
What do we expect?

00:10:22.039 --> 00:10:24.620
Well, light is made out
of little particles,

00:10:24.620 --> 00:10:26.720
so the particles will
go either through one

00:10:26.720 --> 00:10:28.730
of the slits or the other.

00:10:28.730 --> 00:10:31.580
So we are clearly going
to get two bright lines

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:33.950
on some detector,
on some screen,

00:10:33.950 --> 00:10:36.824
behind this double slit.

00:10:36.824 --> 00:10:38.240
This is completely
obvious, right?

00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:41.100
So why bother to
do the experiment?

00:10:41.100 --> 00:10:43.010
But anyway, he did
the experiment anyway.

00:10:43.010 --> 00:10:46.760
He probably didn't have
anything else to do.

00:10:46.760 --> 00:10:50.440
And what he found is
completely different.

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:55.510
He found this pattern of rays,
which are called interferences.

00:10:55.510 --> 00:10:57.460
And interferences
were well known,

00:10:57.460 --> 00:10:59.380
and are very well
known, for instance,

00:10:59.380 --> 00:11:03.040
if you are on a very
quiet pond, and you

00:11:03.040 --> 00:11:04.900
throw two little
pebbles in this pond,

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:06.580
you'll get two waves,
which are going

00:11:06.580 --> 00:11:08.360
to come close to each other.

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:10.530
And when they interact,
you get these waves.

00:11:10.530 --> 00:11:13.580
You get this
interference pattern.

00:11:13.580 --> 00:11:15.880
So like, on that.

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:18.880
So he concluded
that actually life

00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:21.760
is not made out of particles,
but it's made of waves.

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:27.950
So just to make sure that
we keep that in mind,

00:11:27.950 --> 00:11:30.530
because it will be
somewhat important.

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:32.140
If light is made
out of particles,

00:11:32.140 --> 00:11:35.320
we would get a patter like
that-- two bright spots.

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:38.420
If it's made out of waves, we
will get something like that--

00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:41.432
the interferences
that Young observed.

00:11:41.432 --> 00:11:42.265
So he wrote a paper.

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:49.560
And then, he realized
that it's not a good idea

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:51.180
to contradict Newton.

00:11:51.180 --> 00:11:53.100
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:53.100 --> 00:11:54.090
So here is the paper.

00:11:54.090 --> 00:11:56.760
I don't want you to
read it, but I just

00:11:56.760 --> 00:11:59.760
want to show you a
review of his paper.

00:11:59.760 --> 00:12:01.710
And now, I'm an editor
of a bunch of journals,

00:12:01.710 --> 00:12:04.170
so I see reviews like that.

00:12:04.170 --> 00:12:06.570
Maybe not as arrogant.

00:12:06.570 --> 00:12:09.370
But to show you that physicists,
contrary to popular belief,

00:12:09.370 --> 00:12:12.420
are not always nice guys.

00:12:12.420 --> 00:12:15.390
So here is what
this review said--

00:12:15.390 --> 00:12:19.250
"the paper contains nothing
that deserves the name either

00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:22.020
of experiment or
discovery, and it

00:12:22.020 --> 00:12:26.298
is in fact destitute of
every species of merit."

00:12:26.298 --> 00:12:28.926
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:28.926 --> 00:12:30.450
And then, it got personnel.

00:12:30.450 --> 00:12:33.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:37.060
"More fancies, more
unfounded hypotheses,

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:41.140
more gratuitous fictions,
all upon the same field

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:46.850
on which Newton trod, all from
the fertile yet fruitless brain

00:12:46.850 --> 00:12:48.940
of the same eternal Dr. Young.

00:12:48.940 --> 00:12:51.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:51.700 --> 00:12:52.485
This is not nice.

00:12:55.830 --> 00:12:57.950
So yeah.

00:12:57.950 --> 00:12:59.150
So it's tough, right?

00:12:59.150 --> 00:13:01.574
You have this dogma around,
and you try to change it,

00:13:01.574 --> 00:13:02.490
and it's really tough.

00:13:02.490 --> 00:13:05.870
And it took a long, long time
before finally people said,

00:13:05.870 --> 00:13:08.840
maybe Young has something.

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:11.420
And during the
whole 19th century,

00:13:11.420 --> 00:13:12.960
people worked very hard at that.

00:13:12.960 --> 00:13:18.040
And the culmination of this
work was the work of Maxwell--

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:21.490
James Clerk Maxwell--
who explained light

00:13:21.490 --> 00:13:23.530
in terms of
electromagnetic waves.

00:13:23.530 --> 00:13:25.720
I think that Keith Dienes
has talked about that.

00:13:25.720 --> 00:13:29.500
These are electromagnetic waves
which propagate-- surprise--

00:13:29.500 --> 00:13:31.270
at the speed of light.

00:13:31.270 --> 00:13:31.930
OK.

00:13:31.930 --> 00:13:33.340
So this was perfect.

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:35.950
And this is one of the
culminations of 19th century

00:13:35.950 --> 00:13:37.840
physics.

00:13:37.840 --> 00:13:40.450
It's also a boot
camp for theorists.

00:13:40.450 --> 00:13:44.110
This is very hard
physics, and it explains

00:13:44.110 --> 00:13:45.970
a great deal of things.

00:13:45.970 --> 00:13:48.420
And it's wonderful.

00:13:48.420 --> 00:13:50.500
It's wonderful, except
there was just one

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:53.860
small problem with
Maxwell's equations,

00:13:53.860 --> 00:13:56.440
and this theory of light.

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:59.800
And this is something
called blackbody radiation.

00:13:59.800 --> 00:14:03.170
So let me tell you what
blackbody radiation is.

00:14:03.170 --> 00:14:08.990
Blackbody radiation has to
do with the light emitted

00:14:08.990 --> 00:14:11.240
by something called a blackbody.

00:14:11.240 --> 00:14:12.320
So what is a blackbody?

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:14.720
This is what I've
tried to show here.

00:14:14.720 --> 00:14:19.220
It's basically a little
cavity, a hollow cavity,

00:14:19.220 --> 00:14:20.810
which is black for everything.

00:14:20.810 --> 00:14:25.380
So it absorbs all colors
of light perfectly.

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:29.010
Now, of course, if the system
wants to reach a temperature

00:14:29.010 --> 00:14:31.667
and not melt, it has
also to emit this light.

00:14:31.667 --> 00:14:33.750
So there is an equilibrium
between the light which

00:14:33.750 --> 00:14:36.120
is absorbed, and the
light which is emitted.

00:14:36.120 --> 00:14:40.080
Blackbody is that this
works for every color

00:14:40.080 --> 00:14:42.150
in the spectrum of light.

00:14:42.150 --> 00:14:44.700
And then, you can
make a little pinhole

00:14:44.700 --> 00:14:47.250
and see how much
intensity you have

00:14:47.250 --> 00:14:49.450
for different colors
of this light.

00:14:49.450 --> 00:14:52.440
It's called the spectrum
of blackbody radiation.

00:14:52.440 --> 00:14:58.640
And you can measure that, and
you find this result here.

00:14:58.640 --> 00:15:01.690
So on the horizontal axis, I
have the wavelength of light.

00:15:01.690 --> 00:15:04.160
It's just the
color of light, OK.

00:15:04.160 --> 00:15:07.550
And on the vertical
axis, it's the intensity.

00:15:07.550 --> 00:15:09.950
And I have three curves of
different color-- a red curve,

00:15:09.950 --> 00:15:12.020
a yellow curve,
and a blue curve--

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:14.420
for three different
temperatures.

00:15:14.420 --> 00:15:17.630
So it's 3,000 Kelvin.

00:15:17.630 --> 00:15:18.530
You see the peak.

00:15:18.530 --> 00:15:21.320
The most intensity is
around 1 micrometer,

00:15:21.320 --> 00:15:23.540
which is infrared light.

00:15:23.540 --> 00:15:25.280
As you heat up your
cavity, you make

00:15:25.280 --> 00:15:30.110
it 4,000 Kelvin, the peak
of the intensity shifts

00:15:30.110 --> 00:15:34.880
to more visible
light near the red.

00:15:34.880 --> 00:15:37.970
And if it gets even warmer,
it shifts toward the blue.

00:15:37.970 --> 00:15:40.430
These are things that people
can measure extraordinary

00:15:40.430 --> 00:15:42.800
accurately.

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:44.930
This is the blackbody spectrum.

00:15:44.930 --> 00:15:48.730
And the white curve is
the classical theory

00:15:48.730 --> 00:15:50.490
for 5,000 Kelvin--

00:15:50.490 --> 00:15:53.070
the theory of Maxwell.

00:15:53.070 --> 00:15:54.750
And you don't have
to have a Nobel

00:15:54.750 --> 00:16:00.420
Prize to see that the blue
curve and the white curve

00:16:00.420 --> 00:16:02.640
don't quite match.

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:06.630
Now, physicists are
highly trained people.

00:16:06.630 --> 00:16:08.160
We go through
undergraduate school.

00:16:08.160 --> 00:16:09.900
We do four years of
undergraduate school.

00:16:09.900 --> 00:16:11.970
We do a bunch of years
of graduate school.

00:16:11.970 --> 00:16:13.050
We become postdocs.

00:16:13.050 --> 00:16:15.420
We go through tenure
track, and all that.

00:16:15.420 --> 00:16:20.130
So we have really very fancy
technical words to explain

00:16:20.130 --> 00:16:22.460
these kind of problems.

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:26.360
OK, that's the problem, and
this is the technical word.

00:16:26.360 --> 00:16:29.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:34.700 --> 00:16:37.820
So it means we have a problem.

00:16:37.820 --> 00:16:41.450
Everything was perfect, except
for just this one experiment.

00:16:41.450 --> 00:16:43.200
And nobody could throw
away the blackbody,

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:45.950
and the experiments were very
good, and we had a problem.

00:16:45.950 --> 00:16:48.510
So it bothered
people a great deal.

00:16:48.510 --> 00:16:51.440
And one of the folks who
spent a lot of years trying

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:54.710
to figure out what was
going on was a physicist

00:16:54.710 --> 00:16:57.390
in Germany named Max Planck.

00:16:57.390 --> 00:17:01.440
And finally, out
of desperation, he

00:17:01.440 --> 00:17:06.569
came out with a crazy, new
assumption based on nothing.

00:17:06.569 --> 00:17:13.030
He said light is made of
waves, but these waves

00:17:13.030 --> 00:17:15.680
come in little
bundles of energy,

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:18.550
which can have only
discrete values, which

00:17:18.550 --> 00:17:19.930
are called quanta of energy.

00:17:19.930 --> 00:17:21.640
He invented the word
quanta of energy.

00:17:21.640 --> 00:17:24.160
Now, this is what we
would call photons.

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:26.300
It was completely
out of nowhere.

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:29.140
It was just desperation
he came up with this.

00:17:29.140 --> 00:17:32.600
And then, Einstein worked
with this hypothesis.

00:17:32.600 --> 00:17:35.140
He was able to explain
a bunch of other things.

00:17:35.140 --> 00:17:37.630
So suddenly, we were
back in a situation,

00:17:37.630 --> 00:17:40.180
this kind of perfect
compromise, where light

00:17:40.180 --> 00:17:42.040
is both waves and particles.

00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:49.600
So this was quite a big
leap of faith, in a sense,

00:17:49.600 --> 00:17:52.360
but it explained
this blackbody system

00:17:52.360 --> 00:17:54.610
and all kinds of other things.

00:17:54.610 --> 00:17:56.250
And then, there was a prince.

00:17:56.250 --> 00:17:58.570
You know, every story
has to have a prince.

00:17:58.570 --> 00:18:01.220
So we have a French prince.

00:18:01.220 --> 00:18:04.720
And this is Prince
Louis de Broglie.

00:18:04.720 --> 00:18:07.320
And he went one step further.

00:18:07.320 --> 00:18:08.930
He said, well, if
light is made out

00:18:08.930 --> 00:18:13.340
of objects, which are
both waves and particles,

00:18:13.340 --> 00:18:15.680
maybe everything is made
out of waves and particles,

00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:17.980
every particle is
made out of wave--

00:18:17.980 --> 00:18:20.270
has a wave aspect and
a particle aspect.

00:18:20.270 --> 00:18:23.560
For instance, electrons.

00:18:23.560 --> 00:18:25.090
And this was, again, huge.

00:18:25.090 --> 00:18:26.350
It was his PhD thesis.

00:18:26.350 --> 00:18:28.900
He was in his 20s, OK.

00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:35.280
And if you did that, you could
develop some wonderful theory,

00:18:35.280 --> 00:18:39.960
but it was again not clear that
it was right until, in 1927--

00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:41.760
so just 90 years ago--

00:18:41.760 --> 00:18:43.920
there were experiments
done in the United States

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:46.920
by Davisson and Germer, which
actually proved that electrons

00:18:46.920 --> 00:18:49.020
behave like waves.

00:18:49.020 --> 00:18:52.800
So all this story, which
took about 20-25 years,

00:18:52.800 --> 00:18:55.050
lead to the development
of quantum mechanics.

00:18:55.050 --> 00:18:56.670
There are two of
the big heroes--

00:18:56.670 --> 00:19:01.555
Erwin Schrodinger and
Werner Heisenberg.

00:19:01.555 --> 00:19:03.180
Now, you have to
understand, Heisenberg

00:19:03.180 --> 00:19:06.770
was like 25 years
old when he did that.

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:08.820
And Schrodinger was the old guy.

00:19:08.820 --> 00:19:11.400
He was almost 40.

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:12.665
Don't you hate them?

00:19:12.665 --> 00:19:14.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:14.940 --> 00:19:16.500
They have no respect.

00:19:16.500 --> 00:19:19.920
I guess you had to be
really young to be so crazy

00:19:19.920 --> 00:19:22.290
and create, even
invent, this new theory.

00:19:22.290 --> 00:19:22.920
And it worked.

00:19:22.920 --> 00:19:25.650
And quantum mechanics
has been developed

00:19:25.650 --> 00:19:31.080
to an exquisite level
of understanding,

00:19:31.080 --> 00:19:33.530
and it's change your life.

00:19:33.530 --> 00:19:36.990
How has it changed your life?

00:19:36.990 --> 00:19:38.910
If you understand
quantum mechanics,

00:19:38.910 --> 00:19:41.640
if you understand that
electrons are waves,

00:19:41.640 --> 00:19:44.850
you can understand why
some solids are metals,

00:19:44.850 --> 00:19:47.460
some are insulators,
some are semiconductors,

00:19:47.460 --> 00:19:49.970
and all kinds of
things like that.

00:19:49.970 --> 00:19:52.940
And this led to
extraordinary development.

00:19:52.940 --> 00:19:54.800
You would not have
integrated circuits

00:19:54.800 --> 00:19:56.750
if you did not
understand quantum mech--

00:19:56.750 --> 00:19:59.530
if somebody did not
understand quantum mechanics.

00:19:59.530 --> 00:20:03.270
You would also not
have cellphones.

00:20:03.270 --> 00:20:06.792
You would not have a GPS system.

00:20:06.792 --> 00:20:08.000
What else would you not have?

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.040
You would not have the
internet, that's for sure.

00:20:11.040 --> 00:20:13.960
You would not have lasers.

00:20:13.960 --> 00:20:17.480
You would not have
laser surgery.

00:20:17.480 --> 00:20:20.780
If you did not understand
how atoms interact

00:20:20.780 --> 00:20:23.990
with magnetic fields,
or with light,

00:20:23.990 --> 00:20:28.740
you would not have
magnetic resonance imaging.

00:20:28.740 --> 00:20:29.580
Did I get it right?

00:20:29.580 --> 00:20:30.980
I did.

00:20:30.980 --> 00:20:34.180
And you would not
have solar panels.

00:20:34.180 --> 00:20:36.910
So it's really
changing our life, OK?

00:20:36.910 --> 00:20:38.290
Everything we have in this room.

00:20:38.290 --> 00:20:40.790
I don't know how many people
have a cell phone in this room,

00:20:40.790 --> 00:20:42.472
but I would bet
it's more than one.

00:20:42.472 --> 00:20:44.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:44.320 --> 00:20:46.420
And this is all based
on understanding

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:50.110
quantum mechanics, understanding
this wave particle duality.

00:20:50.110 --> 00:20:53.770
Of course, there are
also some bad things.

00:20:53.770 --> 00:20:57.220
And as somebody pointed
out, a single nuclear weapon

00:20:57.220 --> 00:21:00.950
can ruin your whole day.

00:21:00.950 --> 00:21:03.910
But anyway, so this is really
what quantum mechanics has

00:21:03.910 --> 00:21:07.240
done for us, thanks to
people really understanding

00:21:07.240 --> 00:21:10.590
how to play this game.

00:21:10.590 --> 00:21:12.930
But I want to go
back a little bit,

00:21:12.930 --> 00:21:15.660
because now we know
how to do that,

00:21:15.660 --> 00:21:18.960
but do we understand the
real deep implications

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:20.860
of quantum mechanics?

00:21:20.860 --> 00:21:23.580
And this is what I want to spend
a few minutes going back to.

00:21:23.580 --> 00:21:25.890
So I want to go back to
this double slit experiment.

00:21:28.660 --> 00:21:33.380
Because I told
you that electrons

00:21:33.380 --> 00:21:35.430
are particles and
waves, or photons

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:37.490
are particles and waves.

00:21:37.490 --> 00:21:41.552
But I have not told you
how strange that is.

00:21:41.552 --> 00:21:43.510
And now I want to tell
you how strange that is,

00:21:43.510 --> 00:21:47.690
so I'm going to redo the
Thomas Young experiment.

00:21:47.690 --> 00:21:53.000
But instead of sending a beam
of light, or a beam of electrons

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:54.620
through my double
slit, I'm going

00:21:54.620 --> 00:21:57.280
to send one electron a day.

00:21:57.280 --> 00:22:00.252
Or maybe one one
electron every week.

00:22:00.252 --> 00:22:01.460
Or one electron every minute.

00:22:01.460 --> 00:22:03.590
It doesn't matter, but
very rare events, OK.

00:22:03.590 --> 00:22:05.880
One electron, and then you wait.

00:22:05.880 --> 00:22:07.430
And now, we can do
that, because we

00:22:07.430 --> 00:22:10.054
have all these graduate students
who have nothing better to do.

00:22:10.054 --> 00:22:11.180
[LAUGHTER]

00:22:11.180 --> 00:22:14.310
So they can certainly do
this kind of experiment.

00:22:14.310 --> 00:22:16.200
So let's see what happens.

00:22:16.200 --> 00:22:19.090
So what do you
expect will happen?

00:22:19.090 --> 00:22:23.459
Well, what I expect will happen
is now it's just one electron,

00:22:23.459 --> 00:22:25.750
so the electron is going to
go through one of the holes

00:22:25.750 --> 00:22:29.290
and land on the screen,
and I will get a little dot

00:22:29.290 --> 00:22:31.251
on my detector.

00:22:31.251 --> 00:22:31.750
And I do.

00:22:31.750 --> 00:22:33.190
So this is after a week.

00:22:33.190 --> 00:22:35.462
You have seven or eight dots.

00:22:35.462 --> 00:22:38.030
There's no big deal here.

00:22:38.030 --> 00:22:39.960
And then, I can
do it for a month,

00:22:39.960 --> 00:22:42.360
and I get them more dots.

00:22:42.360 --> 00:22:47.790
And then, I'll do it for
a year, and suddenly, wow.

00:22:47.790 --> 00:22:49.980
I get these interferences.

00:22:49.980 --> 00:22:51.150
This is completely crazy.

00:22:51.150 --> 00:22:53.920
You have to understand
this is completely crazy.

00:22:53.920 --> 00:22:57.850
Because I did it one
electron at a time.

00:22:57.850 --> 00:22:58.630
How do they know?

00:23:01.420 --> 00:23:02.980
How do they know?

00:23:02.980 --> 00:23:06.340
Well, I'm a physicist,
so I say, well, I'm

00:23:06.340 --> 00:23:08.050
going to trick these
darn electrons.

00:23:08.050 --> 00:23:10.770
I'm going to check through
which hole they went.

00:23:10.770 --> 00:23:13.870
And I can put a little detector.

00:23:13.870 --> 00:23:17.200
So here, I have my experiment,
I put a magnifying glass--

00:23:17.200 --> 00:23:19.934
actually, it's going to be a
slightly fancier detector--

00:23:19.934 --> 00:23:21.600
and I'm going to just
look through which

00:23:21.600 --> 00:23:24.450
hole this darn electron went.

00:23:24.450 --> 00:23:26.310
We can do that.

00:23:26.310 --> 00:23:28.380
Do the experiment.

00:23:28.380 --> 00:23:31.782
You measure through which
hole your electrons went.

00:23:31.782 --> 00:23:33.730
Boom.

00:23:33.730 --> 00:23:35.638
The interferences disappear.

00:23:42.608 --> 00:23:43.108
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:43.108 --> 00:23:44.104
There's the cat.

00:23:48.610 --> 00:23:50.120
What have we learned?

00:23:50.120 --> 00:23:53.844
Is my electron a
wave or a particle?

00:23:53.844 --> 00:23:56.830
If you look, if you
observe which way

00:23:56.830 --> 00:23:59.220
the light went through,
of the electron,

00:23:59.220 --> 00:24:01.840
it appears to be a particle.

00:24:01.840 --> 00:24:07.120
If you don't look, it
behaves like a wave.

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:12.570
What it means is that
you can change reality

00:24:12.570 --> 00:24:16.950
by deciding what you're
going to look at.

00:24:16.950 --> 00:24:21.510
And this is the new thing that
quantum mechanics does for you.

00:24:21.510 --> 00:24:25.280
It forces you to change your
understanding of reality.

00:24:29.070 --> 00:24:30.270
John Wheeler.

00:24:30.270 --> 00:24:32.970
You may have heard about John
Wheeler in other lectures,

00:24:32.970 --> 00:24:37.516
because John Wheeler was a great
expert at general relativity.

00:24:37.516 --> 00:24:39.140
He coined the word
black hole actually,

00:24:39.140 --> 00:24:41.900
but he was also a great
expert at quantum mechanics.

00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:44.610
And he was also a
magician with words.

00:24:44.610 --> 00:24:50.150
And he coined this sentence
to describe the situation.

00:24:50.150 --> 00:24:55.610
"What we call reality arises
in the last analysis from

00:24:55.610 --> 00:24:59.830
the posing of yes or no
questions and the registering

00:24:59.830 --> 00:25:03.560
of equipment-evoked responses--

00:25:03.560 --> 00:25:07.300
all things physical are
information theoretic

00:25:07.300 --> 00:25:08.644
in origin."

00:25:08.644 --> 00:25:10.310
Here's another way
to say what he said--

00:25:10.310 --> 00:25:13.400
no phenomenon is a
phenomenon until it

00:25:13.400 --> 00:25:17.360
is a recorded phenomenon
brought to a close

00:25:17.360 --> 00:25:21.300
by an irreversible
act of amplification.

00:25:21.300 --> 00:25:24.400
It's a very, very
profound statement.

00:25:24.400 --> 00:25:27.840
Feynman-- everybody has
heard about Feynman--

00:25:27.840 --> 00:25:30.570
put it another way,
which is actually

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:34.350
very important to also digest.

00:25:34.350 --> 00:25:39.170
"It is impossible to explain
this in any classical way.

00:25:39.170 --> 00:25:41.420
It has in it the heart
of quantum mechanics.

00:25:41.420 --> 00:25:46.220
In reality, it contains
the only mystery.

00:25:46.220 --> 00:25:50.000
We cannot make the mystery
go away by explaining it.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:54.780
We can just tell you how it
works, but not why it works."

00:25:54.780 --> 00:25:56.750
So through this wave
particle duality,

00:25:56.750 --> 00:25:59.720
which we use to make transistors
and [? RCs, ?] and all that,

00:25:59.720 --> 00:26:02.660
has actually much more profound
implications in a sense,

00:26:02.660 --> 00:26:07.350
because it forces us to revisit
what we mean by reality.

00:26:07.350 --> 00:26:09.710
And the reality is that I'm
going to be in real trouble

00:26:09.710 --> 00:26:11.450
with time.

00:26:11.450 --> 00:26:13.110
OK.

00:26:13.110 --> 00:26:18.210
So this was my first mystery.

00:26:18.210 --> 00:26:21.220
Remember, I'd said I would
talk about two mysteries?

