I don't want to
impose that on you.

00:26:54.020 --> 00:26:55.890
So I'll have two
virtual assistants.

00:26:55.890 --> 00:27:00.410
And in physics, we used
to call them A and B.

00:27:00.410 --> 00:27:04.100
But then, we decided to be
nice, and we had to be friendly.

00:27:04.100 --> 00:27:07.430
So now we call
them Alice and Bob.

00:27:07.430 --> 00:27:10.670
So I want to introduce
you to Alice and Bob.

00:27:10.670 --> 00:27:14.190
So who should Alice be?

00:27:14.190 --> 00:27:15.360
I think it's pretty obvious.

00:27:15.360 --> 00:27:18.270
Alice should be Alice
from Alice in Wonderland.

00:27:18.270 --> 00:27:21.000
So here is Alice.

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:23.160
And for Bob, we
need somebody who

00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:25.530
is a very distinguished
person, probably

00:27:25.530 --> 00:27:26.880
someone with a Nobel Prize.

00:27:29.750 --> 00:27:34.980
Nobel Prize gives you the kind
of gravitas that you need.

00:27:34.980 --> 00:27:36.740
So here is a Bob
with a Nobel Prize.

00:27:36.740 --> 00:27:40.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:40.580 --> 00:27:42.710
So this is Alice and Bob.

00:27:42.710 --> 00:27:46.460
And they will be with us
for a little while now.

00:27:46.460 --> 00:27:50.260
So let's first do a
very simple experiment.

00:27:50.260 --> 00:27:53.940
We're going to play with coins.

00:27:53.940 --> 00:27:57.390
So we have a bag of coins,
and both Alice and Bob

00:27:57.390 --> 00:28:01.920
take one coin each
out of this bag.

00:28:01.920 --> 00:28:04.870
And then, Alice flies
fly to New York.

00:28:04.870 --> 00:28:08.220
Bob flies to Los Angeles.

00:28:08.220 --> 00:28:10.500
And they start
playing head and tail.

00:28:10.500 --> 00:28:13.830
They start flipping their coin.

00:28:13.830 --> 00:28:15.640
So let's do it once.

00:28:15.640 --> 00:28:23.320
And Alice finds tail, Bob head.

00:28:23.320 --> 00:28:32.160
Do it again, Alice
head, Bob tail.

00:28:32.160 --> 00:28:43.250
Do it again, head, tail, head,
tail, tail, head, head, tail.

00:28:43.250 --> 00:28:44.542
That's what they find.

00:28:44.542 --> 00:28:45.500
This should bother you.

00:28:45.500 --> 00:28:46.291
Does it bother you?

00:28:46.291 --> 00:28:47.744
Yep.

00:28:47.744 --> 00:28:49.700
Good.

00:28:49.700 --> 00:28:52.370
Why does it bother you?

00:28:52.370 --> 00:28:57.210
Because you never find a case
where they get the same thing.

00:28:57.210 --> 00:28:58.430
These are independent coins.

00:28:58.430 --> 00:29:01.430
He took his coin,
she took her coin.

00:29:01.430 --> 00:29:05.230
She went to New York,
he went to Los Angeles.

00:29:05.230 --> 00:29:08.770
There must be many
situations where they both

00:29:08.770 --> 00:29:11.350
flip to head or to tail.

00:29:11.350 --> 00:29:14.840
We don't have any of those here.

00:29:14.840 --> 00:29:20.644
So this is impossible, right?

00:29:20.644 --> 00:29:22.750
This is impossible.

00:29:22.750 --> 00:29:26.290
It was an hour it's impossible.

00:29:26.290 --> 00:29:30.340
But what I'm going to show
you, or try to convince you,

00:29:30.340 --> 00:29:33.100
is that, in quantum mechanics,
this is actually possible.

00:29:36.690 --> 00:29:44.110
Now, Alice comes and says,
"There is no use trying.

00:29:44.110 --> 00:29:46.910
One can't believe
impossible things."

00:29:46.910 --> 00:29:48.440
But fortunately
the Queen of Hearts

00:29:48.440 --> 00:29:53.460
comes and answers, "I daresay
you haven't had much practice.

00:29:53.460 --> 00:29:56.580
When I was your age, I always
did for half an hour a day.

00:29:56.580 --> 00:29:59.700
Sometimes I've believed as
many as six impossible things

00:29:59.700 --> 00:30:01.440
a day."

00:30:01.440 --> 00:30:04.080
All I want you to do is to
believe one impossible thing

00:30:04.080 --> 00:30:04.860
today.

00:30:04.860 --> 00:30:07.290
Or maybe two.

00:30:07.290 --> 00:30:11.690
OK, so let's try to do
some impossible stuff.

00:30:11.690 --> 00:30:15.280
And to do that, I will
tell you something

00:30:15.280 --> 00:30:16.540
that we can do in physics.

00:30:16.540 --> 00:30:19.310
We can do something,
which is called--

00:30:19.310 --> 00:30:22.540
we can create something
called two-state particles.

00:30:22.540 --> 00:30:25.470
Let me tell you a little
bit how this works.

00:30:25.470 --> 00:30:27.200
It's actually very
simple in principle.

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:31.610
In practice, only
experimentalists can do that.

00:30:31.610 --> 00:30:33.450
But basically, the
idea is very simple.

00:30:33.450 --> 00:30:36.530
You take a source of
atoms, maybe cesium atoms

00:30:36.530 --> 00:30:40.010
or silver atoms, and
you put them in an oven.

00:30:40.010 --> 00:30:43.130
And you heat them up until
they start evaporating.

00:30:43.130 --> 00:30:46.160
And some of the atoms are
going to exit from the oven.

00:30:46.160 --> 00:30:48.070
And then, you put
two little holes

00:30:48.070 --> 00:30:50.890
to make a very
nice beam of atoms.

00:30:50.890 --> 00:30:52.730
You can do that.

00:30:52.730 --> 00:30:54.860
And then, you pass
this beam of atoms

00:30:54.860 --> 00:30:59.420
through a magnet, which is a
north pole and a south pole.

00:30:59.420 --> 00:31:03.890
And then, you see where these
atoms land on the screen

00:31:03.890 --> 00:31:06.090
after the magnet.

00:31:06.090 --> 00:31:10.560
And what you will find
is that they will only

00:31:10.560 --> 00:31:15.110
land in two positions,
either up or down.

00:31:15.110 --> 00:31:16.900
OK.

00:31:16.900 --> 00:31:19.700
This is called the
Stern-Gerlach experiment.

00:31:19.700 --> 00:31:22.300
For a given atom, you don't
it will end up or down,

00:31:22.300 --> 00:31:26.110
but they will only
end up or down.

00:31:26.110 --> 00:31:29.260
So this is basically like coins.

00:31:29.260 --> 00:31:31.330
For coins, we had head and tail.

00:31:31.330 --> 00:31:34.120
For these atoms,
we have up or down.

00:31:34.120 --> 00:31:36.500
So in a sense, you can think
of them as quantum coins.

00:31:39.080 --> 00:31:40.820
And one thing that
I also need to tell

00:31:40.820 --> 00:31:43.340
you, because it's
going to be important,

00:31:43.340 --> 00:31:47.060
is that you can rotate the
magnets, and what will happen

00:31:47.060 --> 00:31:48.590
is that you just
rotate the same.

00:31:48.590 --> 00:31:49.840
You still have just two dots.

00:31:49.840 --> 00:31:52.250
They will just be
rotated like the magnet.

00:31:52.250 --> 00:31:55.370
And we are going to use that
later to really confuse things

00:31:55.370 --> 00:31:57.710
even more.

00:31:57.710 --> 00:32:01.940
So these are, if you
want, our quantum coins.

00:32:01.940 --> 00:32:04.810
And these quantum
coins are very strange.

00:32:04.810 --> 00:32:10.070
So classical coins can
have only head or tail.

00:32:10.070 --> 00:32:14.440
Quantum coins can have up
and down at the same time.

00:32:14.440 --> 00:32:16.190
We talked a bit about
the Schrodinger cat,

00:32:16.190 --> 00:32:19.101
which can be alive and dead.

00:32:19.101 --> 00:32:21.350
Well, it's hard to make a
cat which is alive and dead.

00:32:21.350 --> 00:32:25.160
But these quantum coins, we can
really make them up and down

00:32:25.160 --> 00:32:26.580
at the same time.

00:32:26.580 --> 00:32:28.670
So this is a key difference.

00:32:28.670 --> 00:32:31.610
Classical coins have
to be head or tail,

00:32:31.610 --> 00:32:35.560
this can be head and
tail at the same time.

00:32:35.560 --> 00:32:37.090
So now, let's play
with these coins.

00:32:37.090 --> 00:32:40.650
OK, let's do the Alice
and Bob experiment.

00:32:40.650 --> 00:32:44.370
So I'm going to have a
source of these coins.

00:32:44.370 --> 00:32:47.760
And I can send two of
them, because these

00:32:47.760 --> 00:32:49.260
are very special sources.

00:32:49.260 --> 00:32:53.240
You have to work a little
bit at making these sources.

00:32:53.240 --> 00:32:57.230
But you can make these two
quantum coins, these two atoms.

00:32:57.230 --> 00:33:00.140
You can prepare the
system in such a way

00:33:00.140 --> 00:33:05.690
that, if the first one is
up, then the second one

00:33:05.690 --> 00:33:08.030
is down for sure.

00:33:08.030 --> 00:33:12.110
And if the first one is
down, then the second one

00:33:12.110 --> 00:33:13.910
is up for sure.

00:33:13.910 --> 00:33:17.720
You can do that
in atomic physics.

00:33:17.720 --> 00:33:19.310
It's not very hard.

00:33:19.310 --> 00:33:23.120
These are called
entangled particles.

00:33:23.120 --> 00:33:26.960
If one is, the other
one is down for sure.

00:33:26.960 --> 00:33:29.090
That's the thing that was
impossible with the coins

00:33:29.090 --> 00:33:33.290
of Alice and Bob, but with
atoms, you can do that.

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:37.480
And so, if you want to
describe this system,

00:33:37.480 --> 00:33:43.740
you will say that this system
is such that, if one is up,

00:33:43.740 --> 00:33:44.890
the other one is down.

00:33:44.890 --> 00:33:47.940
But remember, they can be up
and down at the same time.

00:33:47.940 --> 00:33:52.620
So we have the system which
is up, down, and down, up.

00:33:52.620 --> 00:33:54.690
So that's the state
of the system,

00:33:54.690 --> 00:33:57.790
to use the jargon
of quantum physics.

00:33:57.790 --> 00:34:00.600
These are entangled particles.

00:34:00.600 --> 00:34:03.435
And now, let's make
some measurements.

00:34:03.435 --> 00:34:05.560
So I'm going to make an
experiment, where I'm going

00:34:05.560 --> 00:34:07.210
to put one of these magnets.

00:34:07.210 --> 00:34:09.110
Remember like we had a
couple of slides ago,

00:34:09.110 --> 00:34:13.270
I'm going to put a magnet
to try to figure out

00:34:13.270 --> 00:34:17.060
if my particle 1 is up or down.

00:34:17.060 --> 00:34:21.000
And let's say I measure
my particle to be up.

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:23.190
So what does it mean?

00:34:23.190 --> 00:34:26.790
It means the second
particle is down for sure.

00:34:26.790 --> 00:34:27.420
Right?

00:34:27.420 --> 00:34:29.580
All these particles
were prepared.

00:34:29.580 --> 00:34:33.409
So once I look, and I discover
that the first particle is up--

00:34:33.409 --> 00:34:35.504
look under the--

00:34:35.504 --> 00:34:39.820
poof, this disappears.

00:34:39.820 --> 00:34:42.400
After I have measured the
state of my first particle,

00:34:42.400 --> 00:34:44.409
the system is now in this state.

00:34:44.409 --> 00:34:48.900
The second particle
is instantly in down.

00:34:48.900 --> 00:34:51.960
And this will be
instantly in down,

00:34:51.960 --> 00:34:54.150
even if the first
particle is in New York,

00:34:54.150 --> 00:34:57.170
the second is in Los Angeles.

00:34:57.170 --> 00:35:02.010
This is what Einstein called
spooky action at a distance.

00:35:02.010 --> 00:35:06.330
Why did he call it spooky
action at a distance?

00:35:06.330 --> 00:35:08.400
Because it was
this instantaneous

00:35:08.400 --> 00:35:11.460
change in the system, and
Einstein, who was no dummy,

00:35:11.460 --> 00:35:13.740
knew that things like
that should not happen,

00:35:13.740 --> 00:35:16.410
because no information
can be transferred faster

00:35:16.410 --> 00:35:18.160
than the speed of light.

00:35:18.160 --> 00:35:19.980
So what's going on here?

00:35:19.980 --> 00:35:24.440
What's going on is
that spooky action

00:35:24.440 --> 00:35:29.930
at a distance conflicts with the
fundamental concept of locality

00:35:29.930 --> 00:35:31.971
in classical physics.

00:35:31.971 --> 00:35:32.845
And that's a problem.

00:35:35.610 --> 00:35:36.990
That's a real problem.

00:35:36.990 --> 00:35:38.760
Now, I have to make
a point very clear.

00:35:38.760 --> 00:35:41.820
It doesn't mean that information
can be transferred faster

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:43.260
than the speed of light.

00:35:43.260 --> 00:35:45.090
But just the state
can be changed faster

00:35:45.090 --> 00:35:49.030
than the speed of light, which
is a different statement.

00:35:49.030 --> 00:35:50.056
OK.

00:35:50.056 --> 00:35:51.720
And that's not all.

00:35:51.720 --> 00:35:53.590
He comes back.

00:35:53.590 --> 00:35:55.811
Einstein never
stops annoying you.

00:35:55.811 --> 00:35:58.220
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:58.220 --> 00:36:02.920
Einstein wrote a very, very
wonderful paper in 1935

00:36:02.920 --> 00:36:05.980
with his colleagues,
Podolsky and Rosen.

00:36:05.980 --> 00:36:09.320
This paper made everybody think.

00:36:09.320 --> 00:36:14.170
And it's almost certainly the
most interesting wrong paper

00:36:14.170 --> 00:36:16.330
in the history of
physics, because it really

00:36:16.330 --> 00:36:19.290
made everybody think.

00:36:19.290 --> 00:36:22.170
And he had a definition of
reality, which I already hinted

00:36:22.170 --> 00:36:26.430
at earlier, which he wrote.

00:36:26.430 --> 00:36:29.010
His definition of reality--

00:36:29.010 --> 00:36:32.100
"If, without in any way
disturbing a system,

00:36:32.100 --> 00:36:34.440
we can predict with
certainty the value

00:36:34.440 --> 00:36:39.770
of a physical quantity,
then this physical quantity

00:36:39.770 --> 00:36:42.500
corresponds to an element
of physical reality."

00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:44.672
So that's what I
said about the dean.

00:36:44.672 --> 00:36:46.130
I don't have to go
touch his beard.

00:36:46.130 --> 00:36:47.510
I know that he has a beard.

00:36:47.510 --> 00:36:49.910
There is an element of
physical reality associated

00:36:49.910 --> 00:36:51.260
with his beard.

00:36:51.260 --> 00:36:53.210
It might be a poor
element of reality,

00:36:53.210 --> 00:36:56.370
but it's an element of really.

00:36:56.370 --> 00:37:01.900
So basically, since
now you know for sure

00:37:01.900 --> 00:37:04.060
what the state of
this particle 2

00:37:04.060 --> 00:37:06.450
is without having
to measure it--

00:37:06.450 --> 00:37:08.740
just the particle that
you didn't look at--

00:37:08.740 --> 00:37:12.160
there is an element of
physical reality associated

00:37:12.160 --> 00:37:15.260
with the state of this particle.

00:37:15.260 --> 00:37:15.800
No question.

00:37:18.590 --> 00:37:20.671
But now you can become nasty.

00:37:20.671 --> 00:37:22.670
And you say, I'm going
to do another experiment.

00:37:22.670 --> 00:37:26.140
Instead of having my
magnets pointing vertically,

00:37:26.140 --> 00:37:29.360
I'm going to rotate
them this way.

00:37:29.360 --> 00:37:31.160
Same experiment,
but now I've change

00:37:31.160 --> 00:37:33.230
the direction of the magnet.

00:37:33.230 --> 00:37:35.360
And obviously, I can
do the same argument,

00:37:35.360 --> 00:37:40.070
and I will also have an element
of physical reality associated

00:37:40.070 --> 00:37:43.412
with the state of this
particle along this direction.

00:37:47.480 --> 00:37:48.740
Makes a lot of sense.

00:37:48.740 --> 00:37:51.350
It should, because it
comes from Einstein.

00:37:51.350 --> 00:37:54.030
Einstein makes a lot of sense.

00:37:54.030 --> 00:37:58.160
But then, there is this fellow
I mentioned earlier, Heisenberg.

00:37:58.160 --> 00:38:01.417
And he said, you can't do
that, not in quantum mechanics.

00:38:01.417 --> 00:38:02.000
This is no-no.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:03.140
It's a big no-no.

00:38:03.140 --> 00:38:06.440
It's called the Heisenberg
uncertainty principle.

00:38:06.440 --> 00:38:09.170
It is fundamental to
quantum mechanics.

00:38:09.170 --> 00:38:12.210
And he says that
you cannot measure--

00:38:12.210 --> 00:38:15.950
I'll use jargon, the spin
is basically this component

00:38:15.950 --> 00:38:17.660
of this particle up and down--

00:38:17.660 --> 00:38:21.710
you cannot measure this thing
in a vertical and a horizontal

00:38:21.710 --> 00:38:23.990
direction at the same time.

00:38:23.990 --> 00:38:26.150
It is not allowed
in quantum mechanics

00:38:26.150 --> 00:38:28.830
to do that with
arbitrary accuracy.

00:38:28.830 --> 00:38:31.280
This is the Heisenberg
uncertainty relation.

00:38:31.280 --> 00:38:32.570
Nobody disputes that.

00:38:32.570 --> 00:38:36.680
It's been tested and
tested and tested.

00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:38.450
So here is Einstein,
who says, there

00:38:38.450 --> 00:38:40.940
must be an element of
physical reality associated

00:38:40.940 --> 00:38:43.670
with the vertical
component, an element

00:38:43.670 --> 00:38:48.810
of physical reality associated
with the horizontal component.

00:38:48.810 --> 00:38:52.150
And Heisenberg says, you can't
measure both at the same time.

00:38:52.150 --> 00:38:54.440
So what is the conclusion?

00:38:54.440 --> 00:38:58.460
The conclusion is that
quantum mechanics does not

00:38:58.460 --> 00:39:02.420
provide the complete
description of physical reality.

00:39:02.420 --> 00:39:05.570
And this is the famous
Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen

00:39:05.570 --> 00:39:07.730
paradox.

00:39:07.730 --> 00:39:10.110
So where does it leave us?

00:39:10.110 --> 00:39:13.220
It leave us with a problem,
which I already showed you

00:39:13.220 --> 00:39:16.130
at the beginning of
this presentation,

00:39:16.130 --> 00:39:20.980
that quantum entanglement
is in conflict

00:39:20.980 --> 00:39:25.000
with two fundamental tenets
of classical physics--

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:28.940
reality and locality.

00:39:28.940 --> 00:39:31.870
And we went through that.

00:39:31.870 --> 00:39:34.636
OK, so that's pretty heavy.

