and some I will do at 45 at 90.

00:40:48.080 --> 00:40:51.150
And I figure my boss will
never see any different.

00:40:51.150 --> 00:40:53.470
So that's what I'm going to do.

00:40:53.470 --> 00:40:55.970
So I can do this
test, and what I

00:40:55.970 --> 00:41:01.440
find is something which may
sound bizarre, but you will see

00:41:01.440 --> 00:41:05.100
is actually completely trivial.

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:06.720
What do we find is
the number of socks

00:41:06.720 --> 00:41:10.200
that can be washed at 0
degree and not at 45 degree

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:13.620
temperature, plus the number
that could be washed at 45

00:41:13.620 --> 00:41:15.900
degrees and not
90 degrees must be

00:41:15.900 --> 00:41:20.520
larger than the number that can
be washed at 0, but not at 90.

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:24.000
Sounds strange, but let me
show you why it's not strange.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:29.070
I have a very beautiful little
picture here, which is actually

00:41:29.070 --> 00:41:30.460
due to Ken and Danny.

00:41:30.460 --> 00:41:33.520
So thank you so much
for figuring that out.

00:41:33.520 --> 00:41:35.310
So here are my socks.

00:41:35.310 --> 00:41:39.600
So green is they passed the
test, red they failed the test.

00:41:39.600 --> 00:41:41.760
So let's look at the
first one, the ones which

00:41:41.760 --> 00:41:46.160
can pass at 0 degree
and not at 45 degrees.

00:41:46.160 --> 00:41:49.030
So we've not made the
test at 90 degree.

00:41:49.030 --> 00:41:51.580
But at 90 degree, either
they would have passed

00:41:51.580 --> 00:41:53.060
or they would not have passed.

00:41:53.060 --> 00:41:57.370
So my pairs of socks on
the left are the same

00:41:57.370 --> 00:42:00.400
as the pair on the right,
except, at 90, they might

00:42:00.400 --> 00:42:02.390
have passed or not have passed.

00:42:02.390 --> 00:42:03.570
OK?

00:42:03.570 --> 00:42:07.360
And I can do the same
for the next test.

00:42:07.360 --> 00:42:10.000
The ones that can
pass at 45 and 90--

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:12.730
these are these guys
here-- but the test at 0

00:42:12.730 --> 00:42:15.110
could be successful or not.

00:42:15.110 --> 00:42:17.290
So this is really what it means.

00:42:17.290 --> 00:42:21.940
And the one at 0 degree is
90 degrees, same thing again.

00:42:21.940 --> 00:42:23.950
The one in the
middle, at 45 degrees,

00:42:23.950 --> 00:42:26.470
could have passed
or not have passed.

00:42:26.470 --> 00:42:30.390
And now, you look at
this bunch of socks,

00:42:30.390 --> 00:42:33.270
and you give them letters,
because we are doing science.

00:42:33.270 --> 00:42:34.075
So we put letters.

00:42:34.075 --> 00:42:35.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:35.700 --> 00:42:38.530
And you see that these guys
here-- the guys B down here--

00:42:38.530 --> 00:42:40.230
it's green, red, red.

00:42:40.230 --> 00:42:44.190
It's the same as the
green, red, red up here.

00:42:44.190 --> 00:42:46.320
And the green, green,
red are the same

00:42:46.320 --> 00:42:48.750
as the green, green,
red up in the middle.

00:42:48.750 --> 00:42:51.600
So you see these two guys are
included in the other two,

00:42:51.600 --> 00:42:53.666
but the other two
have more stuff.

00:42:53.666 --> 00:42:55.290
And therefore, what
is in the first two

00:42:55.290 --> 00:42:59.280
is at least as much as
what is in the third.

00:42:59.280 --> 00:43:04.312
So it actually kind
of makes sense.

00:43:04.312 --> 00:43:06.020
And now, you can make
a great assumption,

00:43:06.020 --> 00:43:07.820
or you can ask the question--

00:43:07.820 --> 00:43:11.180
are particles like socks?

00:43:11.180 --> 00:43:14.710
So you can make the same
estimation with particles.

00:43:14.710 --> 00:43:18.320
You change socks
to little balls,

00:43:18.320 --> 00:43:21.340
and you get exactly
the same thing.

00:43:21.340 --> 00:43:25.350
And this is a very
fundamental theorem,

00:43:25.350 --> 00:43:28.380
which is called Bell's theorem.

00:43:28.380 --> 00:43:30.640
He did it with a
little bit more mass,

00:43:30.640 --> 00:43:33.010
but basically
that's what he did.

00:43:33.010 --> 00:43:34.920
And here is John Bell.

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:40.340
John Bell was an extraordinary
talented theoretical physicist.

00:43:40.340 --> 00:43:41.120
Worked at CERN.

00:43:41.120 --> 00:43:44.270
He was a high energy
physicist, but he also

00:43:44.270 --> 00:43:48.110
played with these foundations
of quantum mechanics.

00:43:48.110 --> 00:43:52.190
And the beauty of this example
with socks and particles

00:43:52.190 --> 00:43:56.240
is that this is something that
you can test experimentally.

00:43:56.240 --> 00:43:58.220
The EPR paradox,
for a long time,

00:43:58.220 --> 00:44:01.340
folks thought that it was
more or less philosophy.

00:44:01.340 --> 00:44:04.400
But now, you can test these
things experimentally.

00:44:04.400 --> 00:44:08.850
And if the particles don't
behave like sock's, it

00:44:08.850 --> 00:44:10.510
means something fundamental.

00:44:10.510 --> 00:44:15.330
It means that quantum
physics cannot be represented

00:44:15.330 --> 00:44:18.260
by a classical
picture of physics.

00:44:18.260 --> 00:44:22.190
Or if you want to put
in more fancy words,

00:44:22.190 --> 00:44:25.400
if this test is
failed, it rules out

00:44:25.400 --> 00:44:28.000
of description of
quantum mechanics

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:30.380
by a local realistic theory.

00:44:30.380 --> 00:44:32.120
And again, the beauty
of Bell's theorem

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:34.760
is that, suddenly, you can
actually do the experiment.

00:44:34.760 --> 00:44:36.490
So the experiment was done.

00:44:36.490 --> 00:44:41.000
Started in the late
'70s and early '80s.

00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:43.990
And the way you do the
experiment is pretty much what

00:44:43.990 --> 00:44:47.600
I did before, except that now,
having testing on just one

00:44:47.600 --> 00:44:51.575
side, you put one side at 90
degrees and one at 45 degrees

00:44:51.575 --> 00:44:53.950
to do the two temperatures if
you want the two angles now

00:44:53.950 --> 00:44:57.850
for the spins, and you can
still do this experiment.

00:44:57.850 --> 00:44:58.820
And you can count.

00:44:58.820 --> 00:45:00.320
And these experiments
have been done

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:02.740
better and better
and better, and they

00:45:02.740 --> 00:45:04.880
are becoming more and
more sophisticated,

00:45:04.880 --> 00:45:08.150
and with less and
less systematic error.

00:45:08.150 --> 00:45:14.760
And the result is, if the
particles behave like socks,

00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:17.970
you will have this inequality.

00:45:17.970 --> 00:45:20.710
And in quantum mechanics,
you can actually

00:45:20.710 --> 00:45:24.130
calculate, or measure,
these probabilities,

00:45:24.130 --> 00:45:29.090
and you'll find that
the first one is 0.07.

00:45:29.090 --> 00:45:30.850
The second one is 0.07.

00:45:30.850 --> 00:45:33.140
And the third is 0.25.

00:45:33.140 --> 00:45:39.690
And 0.25 is larger than 0.14.

00:45:39.690 --> 00:45:40.700
So this is violated.

00:45:43.520 --> 00:45:46.076
So particles don't
behave like socks.

00:45:46.076 --> 00:45:48.020
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:48.020 --> 00:45:54.720
And basically, it shows that
quantum mechanics is not

00:45:54.720 --> 00:45:56.295
a local realistic theory.

00:45:59.100 --> 00:46:00.120
So Feynman.

00:46:00.120 --> 00:46:02.370
Feynman is back.

00:46:02.370 --> 00:46:04.800
And he made another
statement about the result

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:10.190
of this experiment, which is the
statement that you should make,

00:46:10.190 --> 00:46:12.380
that we should all make.

00:46:12.380 --> 00:46:14.048
This is why we drink.

00:46:14.048 --> 00:46:15.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:15.260 --> 00:46:19.910
"Quantum mechanics
describes nature as absurd

00:46:19.910 --> 00:46:22.400
from the point of
view of common sense.

00:46:22.400 --> 00:46:25.580
And yet it fully
agrees with experiment.

00:46:25.580 --> 00:46:28.970
So I hope you can accept
nature as she is--

00:46:28.970 --> 00:46:31.450
absurd."

00:46:31.450 --> 00:46:34.160
And unfortunately, that's true.

00:46:34.160 --> 00:46:38.520
It's completely contrary
to our common intuition.

00:46:38.520 --> 00:46:40.740
We're just not hardwired
to understand what

00:46:40.740 --> 00:46:42.420
nature is at the quantum level.

00:46:45.210 --> 00:46:48.000
Now, there is another
quote I want to make.

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:51.790
This is from somebody
named Alain Aspect.

00:46:51.790 --> 00:46:55.130
Alain Aspect is a remarkable
figure in this whole story,

00:46:55.130 --> 00:46:56.930
because he started
to do experiments

00:46:56.930 --> 00:46:58.790
as a graduate student.

00:46:58.790 --> 00:47:00.380
I know him quite well.

00:47:00.380 --> 00:47:03.320
And he told me that, when he
started to learn about that,

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:05.100
he went to visit John Bell.

00:47:05.100 --> 00:47:07.760
Alain Aspect is in Paris,
John Bell was in Geneva.

00:47:07.760 --> 00:47:10.070
And he told him, I
want to do experiments.

00:47:10.070 --> 00:47:13.700
And John Bell asked him, do
you have a permanent job?

00:47:13.700 --> 00:47:15.140
And Alain Aspect was a student.

00:47:15.140 --> 00:47:16.025
He said, no I don't.

00:47:16.025 --> 00:47:18.770
He said, don't do it.

00:47:18.770 --> 00:47:21.560
Because it was the best
way not to get the job.

00:47:21.560 --> 00:47:25.010
But Allain Aspect, being who he
is, decided to go ahead anyway.

00:47:25.010 --> 00:47:28.190
And he's become the world
expert on this business.

00:47:28.190 --> 00:47:30.350
I'm sure he will
get a Nobel Prize.

00:47:30.350 --> 00:47:33.500
The other reason I want to
show this picture of Allain

00:47:33.500 --> 00:47:39.680
is that he makes the best
duck confit in the world.

00:47:39.680 --> 00:47:41.450
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:41.450 --> 00:47:44.690
And he has a cellar with
over a thousand bottles.

00:47:44.690 --> 00:47:46.700
And I want to be invited
back in his house.

00:47:46.700 --> 00:47:48.680
[LAUGHTER]

00:47:48.680 --> 00:47:53.600
And what Allain said is, "By
closing"-- so it was in 2015,

00:47:53.600 --> 00:47:55.850
he said that, when these
perfect experiments

00:47:55.850 --> 00:47:59.000
on the violation of Bellian
inequalities came out.

00:47:59.000 --> 00:48:01.190
And Allain said, "By
closing these loopholes"--

00:48:01.190 --> 00:48:03.640
so it was still bothering
people-- "at once,

00:48:03.640 --> 00:48:07.220
three experimental tests of
Bell's inequalities remove

00:48:07.220 --> 00:48:11.570
the last doubts that we should
renounce local realism."

00:48:11.570 --> 00:48:14.630
And the other key point that he
made, that other people knew,

00:48:14.630 --> 00:48:17.870
and this brings us to the
second quantum revolution,

00:48:17.870 --> 00:48:23.330
is that these experiments
opened the door to new quantum

00:48:23.330 --> 00:48:25.340
information technologies.

00:48:25.340 --> 00:48:27.110
And I want us to spend
about three or four

00:48:27.110 --> 00:48:29.210
minutes-- where is Bo?

00:48:29.210 --> 00:48:30.660
Bo is checking time.

00:48:30.660 --> 00:48:35.030
Bo, I think it's
time for a break.

00:48:35.030 --> 00:48:39.260
So I want to show you
one simple example of how

00:48:39.260 --> 00:48:43.230
this new, more profound,
understanding of the way

00:48:43.230 --> 00:48:45.840
to manipulate the laws
of quantum mechanics

00:48:45.840 --> 00:48:47.340
will lead us to
new technologies.

00:48:47.340 --> 00:48:52.275
The example I want to mention
is quantum cryptography.

00:48:52.275 --> 00:48:54.420
Now, we all know
about cryptography.

00:48:54.420 --> 00:48:56.100
This is these
techniques which make

00:48:56.100 --> 00:48:58.470
us able to communicate
with our iPhones,

00:48:58.470 --> 00:49:01.410
without everybody
eavesdropping on us.

00:49:01.410 --> 00:49:03.120
So the idea is--

00:49:03.120 --> 00:49:04.680
let's say, here is Alice again.

00:49:04.680 --> 00:49:06.930
She wants to
communicate with Bob.

00:49:06.930 --> 00:49:09.420
She wants to send him
this beautiful message--

00:49:09.420 --> 00:49:15.120
very romantic message-- and
she doesn't want anybody else

00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:16.500
to hear this message.

00:49:16.500 --> 00:49:19.070
So the way cryptography
works is that you

00:49:19.070 --> 00:49:22.110
invent a key, which
allows you to encrypt

00:49:22.110 --> 00:49:25.720
your system, and the keys
that she uses, in this case,

00:49:25.720 --> 00:49:28.650
is this thing in yellow here.

00:49:28.650 --> 00:49:31.650
And the trick is that Bob
also needs to know this key.

00:49:34.330 --> 00:49:35.330
OK, here's the key.

00:49:35.330 --> 00:49:36.880
And then, once he
has the key, she

00:49:36.880 --> 00:49:38.710
can just call him
with the message.

00:49:38.710 --> 00:49:41.230
No, first, she has to
encrypt this message.

00:49:41.230 --> 00:49:43.120
And the way she does
it here is very simple.

00:49:43.120 --> 00:49:47.110
If two numbers are the same, it
becomes a 0 in the encryption.

00:49:47.110 --> 00:49:50.140
If the two numbers are
different, it becomes a 1.

00:49:50.140 --> 00:49:52.630
And then, she sends
encrypted message.

00:49:52.630 --> 00:49:57.790
And he uses the same rule
to recover his message.

00:49:57.790 --> 00:49:59.680
That's how it works.

00:49:59.680 --> 00:50:04.330
And the trick of cryptography
is to make these keys very safe,

00:50:04.330 --> 00:50:07.180
hard to break,
and hard to steal.

00:50:07.180 --> 00:50:09.310
But it's always a problem.

00:50:09.310 --> 00:50:11.170
And people are
spending actually a lot

00:50:11.170 --> 00:50:14.170
of money making safe
encryption, and trying

00:50:14.170 --> 00:50:16.390
to break safe encryption.

00:50:16.390 --> 00:50:22.400
So quantum entanglement
allows actually to beat this.

00:50:22.400 --> 00:50:26.050
And the way it works
is very simple.

00:50:26.050 --> 00:50:29.100
Instead of having a key
that you share by telephone,

00:50:29.100 --> 00:50:32.040
or by meeting under
a tree or something,

00:50:32.040 --> 00:50:35.650
you do an experiment with
these entangled particles.

00:50:35.650 --> 00:50:38.640
So let's say Alice is
going to create sources

00:50:38.640 --> 00:50:41.220
of entangled particles,
and she gets one of them,

00:50:41.220 --> 00:50:43.170
and Bob gets the other one.

00:50:43.170 --> 00:50:46.080
And now, they're
both going to measure

00:50:46.080 --> 00:50:51.220
the state of their particle,
if it's up or down.

00:50:51.220 --> 00:50:55.090
And if the analyzers-- if the
magnets are aligned the same

00:50:55.090 --> 00:50:59.410
way, they know for
sure that, if they--

00:50:59.410 --> 00:51:02.110
Alice knows for sure,
if she measures up,

00:51:02.110 --> 00:51:04.392
Bob will have down.

00:51:04.392 --> 00:51:09.010
But if they are not
aligned the same way,

00:51:09.010 --> 00:51:11.230
then there is
nothing they can say.

00:51:11.230 --> 00:51:13.780
They don't know what the
answer of the other will be.

00:51:13.780 --> 00:51:16.630
So all they need to do is
to do this experiment--

00:51:16.630 --> 00:51:18.640
this measurement--
many, many times,

00:51:18.640 --> 00:51:21.310
and then they get on
the phone and they share

00:51:21.310 --> 00:51:23.662
the alignments of their magnet.

00:51:23.662 --> 00:51:25.870
And maybe they will say,
oh, in the first experiment,

00:51:25.870 --> 00:51:28.750
both magnets were
aligned the same way.

00:51:28.750 --> 00:51:31.844
So I know what I measured,
therefore I know what he has.

00:51:31.844 --> 00:51:34.260
And in the second one, they
were not aligned the same way,

00:51:34.260 --> 00:51:35.650
so we discard them.

00:51:35.650 --> 00:51:41.740
And they keep doing, and you
keep only the results when

00:51:41.740 --> 00:51:45.490
your magnets were aligned, so
you get your nice entanglement.

00:51:45.490 --> 00:51:47.370
And you build a key this way.

00:51:47.370 --> 00:51:49.860
You never have to tell the
result of your experiment.

00:51:49.860 --> 00:51:53.930
You just have to say the
setting of your magnet.

00:51:53.930 --> 00:51:59.560
So can you break this way
of transferring information?

00:51:59.560 --> 00:52:02.180
It turns out--
that's what I said.

00:52:02.180 --> 00:52:07.160
So it turns out that
you can't in principle.

00:52:07.160 --> 00:52:09.030
And the reason you
can't is twofold.

00:52:09.030 --> 00:52:12.650
The first one is the Heisenberg
uncertainty principle,

00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:14.850
which we talked about.

00:52:14.850 --> 00:52:17.250
If somebody tries to make a
measurement on your system,

00:52:17.250 --> 00:52:19.920
it will perturb your system
in quantum mechanics.

00:52:19.920 --> 00:52:23.592
So we'd know for sure that
somebody was eavesdropping.

00:52:23.592 --> 00:52:25.050
So the eavesdropper
will say, well,

00:52:25.050 --> 00:52:26.716
I'm just going to
duplicate your system.

00:52:26.716 --> 00:52:28.640
I'm going to make a
clone of your system,

00:52:28.640 --> 00:52:30.230
make my measurements
on your system,

00:52:30.230 --> 00:52:32.050
and then I will know
what you have done,

00:52:32.050 --> 00:52:33.660
and I will steal your key.

00:52:33.660 --> 00:52:35.240
And you can't do that either.

00:52:35.240 --> 00:52:37.160
I don't have time
to go through that.

00:52:37.160 --> 00:52:40.396
You can't do that, because
there is a theorem, which

00:52:40.396 --> 00:52:42.020
is called the no-cloning
theorem, which

00:52:42.020 --> 00:52:44.540
says that you can only
duplicate the system by losing

00:52:44.540 --> 00:52:47.010
all information.

00:52:47.010 --> 00:52:51.240
So the result is that
quantum key distribution--

00:52:51.240 --> 00:52:53.110
that's the best
word used for that--

00:52:53.110 --> 00:52:54.930
is completely safe.

00:52:54.930 --> 00:52:56.880
And this is one of
the first applications

00:52:56.880 --> 00:52:58.482
in the second
quantum revolution.

00:52:58.482 --> 00:53:00.690
There are several companies
which sell these systems,

00:53:00.690 --> 00:53:02.692
to banks mostly.

00:53:02.692 --> 00:53:03.650
There is one in Geneva.

00:53:03.650 --> 00:53:04.608
There is one in Vienna.

00:53:04.608 --> 00:53:06.730
There is one in New York.

00:53:06.730 --> 00:53:09.712
And so I was talking
about that with Dean Ruiz.

00:53:09.712 --> 00:53:11.670
And he says, that's really
cool, because now we

00:53:11.670 --> 00:53:13.045
could have the
secret information

00:53:13.045 --> 00:53:15.670
all around the world.

00:53:15.670 --> 00:53:18.700
And I had to tell
him, not so fast.

00:53:18.700 --> 00:53:23.240
Not so fast, because
it's actually hard.

00:53:23.240 --> 00:53:26.080
And it's so hard that the
world record right now

00:53:26.080 --> 00:53:28.900
of how far you can actually
transmit quantum information

00:53:28.900 --> 00:53:32.160
this way is 90 miles.

00:53:32.160 --> 00:53:37.650
And there is a dream to actually
have this global quantum

00:53:37.650 --> 00:53:40.590
communication, but it
doesn't work so far.

00:53:40.590 --> 00:53:43.460
And why doesn't it work?

00:53:43.460 --> 00:53:46.570
It turns out that, if you
want to make these experiments

00:53:46.570 --> 00:53:48.270
at very small
scales in your lab--

00:53:48.270 --> 00:53:50.050
on the tabletop in your lab--

00:53:50.050 --> 00:53:51.470
it's not too hard to do.

00:53:51.470 --> 00:53:53.740
But the bigger you want
to do the experiment,

00:53:53.740 --> 00:53:56.570
the harder it becomes.

00:53:56.570 --> 00:54:01.560
And it may just be impossible
to do a global communication

00:54:01.560 --> 00:54:02.060
system.

00:54:02.060 --> 00:54:03.830
We just don't know.

00:54:03.830 --> 00:54:06.830
So this begs actually
a couple of questions,

00:54:06.830 --> 00:54:12.130
which bring the cat back.

00:54:12.130 --> 00:54:14.130
So we know how to do
these quantum systems

00:54:14.130 --> 00:54:16.610
when they are somewhat small.

00:54:16.610 --> 00:54:18.960
140 kilometers is
not completely small,

00:54:18.960 --> 00:54:21.560
but it's not very big either.

00:54:21.560 --> 00:54:25.160
So this begs the
question-- why don't we

00:54:25.160 --> 00:54:27.440
live in a quantum world?

00:54:27.440 --> 00:54:31.016
Why does it look like
reality is the way we've--

00:54:31.016 --> 00:54:32.720
we have this intuition for that?

00:54:35.390 --> 00:54:38.750
If quantum theory is a
more fundamental theory

00:54:38.750 --> 00:54:41.930
than classical theory,
why does everyday word

00:54:41.930 --> 00:54:44.440
appear as classical?

00:54:44.440 --> 00:54:49.500
Another related question is,
are we fooling ourselves?

00:54:49.500 --> 00:54:51.630
Quantum mechanics was
actually developed

00:54:51.630 --> 00:54:56.190
to describe atoms and photons
at the microscopic level.

00:54:56.190 --> 00:54:58.020
We've pushed it very hard.

00:54:58.020 --> 00:55:02.120
But is it really the
fundamental theory?

00:55:02.120 --> 00:55:04.640
To which extents are
these laws applicable

00:55:04.640 --> 00:55:07.740
in macroscopic systems?

00:55:07.740 --> 00:55:12.240
And a related question is, are
there fundamental limitations

00:55:12.240 --> 00:55:14.950
to quantum entanglement?

00:55:14.950 --> 00:55:17.680
Not practical, but
fundamental limitations.

00:55:17.680 --> 00:55:22.300
Or can we, in
principle, prepare a cat

00:55:22.300 --> 00:55:24.670
in a state where it
is both alive and dead

00:55:24.670 --> 00:55:26.140
at the same time?

00:55:26.140 --> 00:55:28.910
So these are very
profound questions.

00:55:28.910 --> 00:55:35.164
And these are questions
which bother many physicists.

00:55:35.164 --> 00:55:37.080
And there are two
approaches to this question.

00:55:37.080 --> 00:55:41.200
There is what is called the
shut up and calculate kind

00:55:41.200 --> 00:55:43.270
of physicist.

00:55:43.270 --> 00:55:47.260
This sounds pejorative,
but it's not really.

00:55:47.260 --> 00:55:50.950
It's the way that most
physicists do physics.

00:55:50.950 --> 00:55:53.540
We do our calculations.

00:55:53.540 --> 00:55:56.440
We take our system that we want
to behave quantum mechanically,

00:55:56.440 --> 00:55:58.480
but we know that
it's not isolated.

00:55:58.480 --> 00:56:00.880
It's surrounded by
the rest of the world,

00:56:00.880 --> 00:56:04.940
and it's always coupled somehow
to the rest of the world.

00:56:04.940 --> 00:56:07.240
And it turns out that,
the bigger your system,

00:56:07.240 --> 00:56:10.840
the harder it is to isolate
it from the rest of the world.

00:56:10.840 --> 00:56:12.730
And this coupling to
the rest of the world

00:56:12.730 --> 00:56:17.500
tends to make the systems
behave more classically.

00:56:17.500 --> 00:56:19.210
So this is kind of
the practical-- the

00:56:19.210 --> 00:56:21.640
shut up and calculate--
where you don't really

00:56:21.640 --> 00:56:26.004
try to understand fundamentally
what the question might be.

00:56:26.004 --> 00:56:27.670
And then, there are
the other physicists

00:56:27.670 --> 00:56:29.503
who actually try to
understand this question

00:56:29.503 --> 00:56:31.090
in a fundamental way.

00:56:31.090 --> 00:56:32.410
And they are working very hard.

00:56:32.410 --> 00:56:36.720
And they're also developing
experiments jointly with theory

00:56:36.720 --> 00:56:39.570
to try to figure out if there
is something fundamental here.

00:56:39.570 --> 00:56:42.840
There are some ideas,
from Penrose and others,

00:56:42.840 --> 00:56:46.290
about the role of gravity
in making systems classical.

00:56:46.290 --> 00:56:47.040
But we don't know.

00:56:47.040 --> 00:56:49.350
So I'm going to finish
my talk, essentially

00:56:49.350 --> 00:56:51.810
like most of the talks
have been finished,

00:56:51.810 --> 00:56:53.820
by a big question mark.

00:56:53.820 --> 00:56:55.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:55.080 --> 00:56:58.470
And this is pretty much
always the same in physics.

00:56:58.470 --> 00:57:01.380
You always answer
some questions,

00:57:01.380 --> 00:57:05.430
and open more problems,
more questions.

00:57:05.430 --> 00:57:09.730
But I'm not completely
finished, because I

00:57:09.730 --> 00:57:13.660
was told that I should also try
to summarize a little bit what

00:57:13.660 --> 00:57:14.800
we have all learned.

00:57:14.800 --> 00:57:18.090
So it's two minutes.

00:57:18.090 --> 00:57:18.640
More or less.

00:57:21.280 --> 00:57:22.806
He's trying to kick me out.

00:57:22.806 --> 00:57:24.790
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:24.790 --> 00:57:27.130
So what have we learned?

00:57:27.130 --> 00:57:31.670
And again, Einstein
comes to the rescue.

00:57:31.670 --> 00:57:34.860
Einstein said so many
very profound things.

00:57:34.860 --> 00:57:37.790
And one of the things he
said is that "no amount

00:57:37.790 --> 00:57:41.780
of experimentation can
ever prove me right,

00:57:41.780 --> 00:57:43.880
but a single experiment
can prove me wrong."

00:57:43.880 --> 00:57:47.890
And we had one example of that,
with this blackbody radiation.

00:57:47.890 --> 00:57:49.520
People did all
these experiments--

00:57:49.520 --> 00:57:54.350
Maxwell was great-- the view,
the wave nature of light

00:57:54.350 --> 00:57:55.370
was perfect.

00:57:55.370 --> 00:57:59.930
But there was this one
experiment that didn't fit,

00:57:59.930 --> 00:58:02.720
and it changed everything.

00:58:02.720 --> 00:58:05.540
It forced people to
invent quantum mechanics,

00:58:05.540 --> 00:58:08.210
this new view of
reality and all that.

00:58:08.210 --> 00:58:10.930
So this is absolutely
true and profound,

00:58:10.930 --> 00:58:18.340
that one experiment can force
you to revisit everything.

00:58:18.340 --> 00:58:22.100
And this is exactly those
experiments that we like.

00:58:22.100 --> 00:58:26.510
And this is why people will
do LHC, to push the limits.

00:58:26.510 --> 00:58:30.430
This is why people do
gravitational wave detection.

00:58:30.430 --> 00:58:33.590
This is the motivation,
to push the theories,

00:58:33.590 --> 00:58:36.641
to push until we have
a place where it fails.

00:58:36.641 --> 00:58:39.140
Because that's-- when it fails--
that we can hopefully learn

00:58:39.140 --> 00:58:41.720
something fundamentally new.

00:58:41.720 --> 00:58:46.800
Now, I should say that this
is not always an easy job.

00:58:46.800 --> 00:58:49.490
It can be quite
humbling, because we

00:58:49.490 --> 00:58:52.360
have our preconceived
view of things,

00:58:52.360 --> 00:58:55.220
and we have to change it.

00:58:55.220 --> 00:58:57.629
And my son, who is
a very wise man,

00:58:57.629 --> 00:58:59.420
once told me that there
are only two things

00:58:59.420 --> 00:59:01.460
that academics don't like.

00:59:01.460 --> 00:59:03.320
The first one is the
current situation,

00:59:03.320 --> 00:59:05.043
and the second one is change.

00:59:05.043 --> 00:59:07.004
[LAUGHTER]

00:59:08.360 --> 00:59:09.380
So there we go.

00:59:09.380 --> 00:59:11.490
OK.

00:59:11.490 --> 00:59:13.460
So we have this problem here.

00:59:13.460 --> 00:59:15.980
But on the other
hand, the payoff

00:59:15.980 --> 00:59:18.140
can be quite extraordinary.

00:59:18.140 --> 00:59:20.030
And we have seen some
of this payoff today,

00:59:20.030 --> 00:59:22.410
and in the other
lectures as well.

00:59:22.410 --> 00:59:28.430
So this unknown, and in being
in a situation of ignorance,

00:59:28.430 --> 00:59:30.860
is actually what
physicists strive for.

00:59:30.860 --> 00:59:33.200
I was preparing this slide
and I was talking to my wife,

00:59:33.200 --> 00:59:35.840
and she said, do you really
want to use the word ignorance,

00:59:35.840 --> 00:59:39.210
because ignorance has
a bad connotation?

00:59:39.210 --> 00:59:40.550
But it's not.

00:59:40.550 --> 00:59:41.650
It should not be.

00:59:41.650 --> 00:59:42.150
OK?

00:59:42.150 --> 00:59:45.650
Ignorance is just an
excuse to understand

00:59:45.650 --> 00:59:47.480
what we don't understand.

00:59:47.480 --> 00:59:49.310
So ignorance, in this sense--

00:59:49.310 --> 00:59:50.900
in this very narrow sense--

00:59:50.900 --> 00:59:56.300
is actually what we strive to
figure out, and to clear up.

00:59:56.300 --> 00:59:58.850
This is really what
keeps us going.

00:59:58.850 --> 01:00:01.662
And this is why I think
there is no better job.

01:00:01.662 --> 01:00:02.620
So thank you very much.

01:00:02.620 --> 01:00:05.370
[APPLAUSE]

